title: For Sale:  Bulk Ammo - Most Common Calibers - 100-Round Brick Deals
postcontent:
Greetings Armslisters,




I have just opened the doors to Vexxxer Munitions(metaphorically; we don't actually have doors yet), and to celebrate I am posting the current stock of ammunition on Armslist, three weeks before our scheduled 'opening' ceremony, here in lovely Portland, OR. I should note right off the bat that this is an online-only store; we do not have a physical office address for one to come pick up ammunition, at least not yet. But you're not here to listen to ramblings about a green-as-grass munitions company, you're here to buy ammunition!


All ammunition is priced and sold in sets of 100 rounds. Shipping will be determined based on location and amount of rounds you want; buying more will end up saving you money, as I can pack them all into a single box, instead of 100 rounds per small box. 

I also offer a 'penny-round' discount for orders of 1,000 rounds or more. At the 1,000 round mark, I take off a penny per round. It's not a huge discount, granted, but if you are planning on shooting a lot anyways, it will save you a fair bit of cash to buy in large quantities. It also makes it much easier on my end logistically, and thus the savings fall directly to the consumer. I try every day to get the best possible deal for the end-customer, in this case, you.


While I do not yet have ALL calibers(we do plan to carry all as soon as is practical), I do have the most commonly shot rounds in America, according to the 2013 arms industry census. I chose to maintain healthy stockpiles of common calibers, rather than create a single brick per caliber, and have to fight to keep them stocked. So, without further preamble, I currently have in stock:


-Tula .45ACP


-Wolf 7.62x39mm


-Silver Bear .223/5.56 NATO


-Winchester Super-X 12GA, Buck-shot


-Bulgarian 7.62x54R, Silver-Tipped [CORROSIVE]


[A quick word on the corrosive ammunition; I am a huge Mosin fan, if you need any advice or assistance in keeping your Mosin pristine, while using the vastly cheaper surplus ammunition(the secret is boiling water), don't hestitate to send me an email. I'm more than happy to help out fellow gun enthusiasts, and Mosiners in particular]


I will be taking special notice of obtaining 9mm especially, as well as .22LR, .308, 10GA rounds as soon as possible, I know that I am missing these very common calibers. But as I said before I'd rather have a healthy stockpile of fewer calibers; the last thing I want is for someone to contact me, and me to be fresh out of any rounds they were looking to buy.



PROCESS:


To order(while our website is being constructed, at least) is very simple; email me with how many rounds you would like, of what caliber. I will require a state or military-issued ID as proof of age (sorry kids, no bullets for you!). From there, I will send you a shipping quote, NOT an estimate. There is an important distinction there; estimates can change, quotes will not. Most ammunition companies use an estimator, and charge you the final price halfway through the process, whether or not the estimate was correct. As I am not trying to profit off both the ammunition and shipping, I do not play the 'estimate' game; if I make a mistake, I will eat the cost; what I quote is what you pay, no exceptions. I'd rather lose money and keep a customer, and keep money and lose a customer.


Once we have the final cost and a formalized request for rounds, I will send you an invoice via Paypal. Once payment is received, you will receive an email from Paypal with the tracking number and current status of your order. Unfortunately, as many of you are no doubt aware, munitions by law MUST travel via ground, otherwise known as snail-mail. So please, factor in at least a week for shipping. That being said, I will ship the same day generally that your order is placed, and on rare occasions the next day. I discount Sunday completely, as no shipping company works on Sundays, much to the world's chagrin.


[For the unfamiliar: Paypal is an escrow service that watches over the transaction, protecting both you and I in exchange for a small fee from me. It is a completely free service for you, and takes about 5 minutes to create an account.]


From that point, all you have to do is wait. Your package will arrive(please notify me when it does; I'm timing various shipping companies to find the fastest ground transport. Also email me if there is something wrong; I'm here for my customers, if there's a problem, I want to know about it), and then all you need to do is go out and have a blast! No pun intended.



Building A Better Business:


Before I wrap up, a word on pricing. I am fully aware that the prices are high, and I am working on it. The bottleneck at this moment is waiting for the various munition factories to analyze and accept my business identification, to confirm that yes, I am a business in the realm of ammunition, and no, I am not just some guy trying to buy 10,000 rounds of ammunition for his 'hunting' trips. Prices and ammunition availability are different for licensed businesses and private citizens. Expect to see prices drop slightly within a month, and drop significantly within 7 months. It may be sooner but I'd rather be conservative in my estimates. The ads will change the very hour I get confirmation from the factories.




Feel free to email me with any questions, comments or concerns you might have. I hope to have a long business career supplying Americans with all their favorite calibers(please note I cannot ship international, at all, by law. Would if I could, but I can't, so I shan't). 


And, as a squeaky-clean, brand-new company, I would be remiss in my duties if I did not ask the customer; if you have any ideas or thoughts on how to run it more efficiently, cut down on shipping time, make the process easier for the customer, etc, please, my email is always open, and I check it multiple times a day. I would also love to hear your opinions on the 'brick' system, as well as my 'can' system that will go into effect next month. If I may tug on your ear a moment longer:

-I plan to have two basic types of product; bricks of 100 rounds, and ammo cans(with number of rounds dependent on caliber). So for example, 300 7.62x54R rounds fit perfectly into a .30 caliber ammunition can, and pricing would be based on how many rounds are included(the cans are free, a thank you for your business). The cans are all brand-new, un-stenciled; I chose this method to allow you to use them for other rounds and not have confusing stenciling on each box(claiming your ammo can full of 9mm is in fact 40mm explosive rounds, for example). I also chose to put the company brand on the back of the can, as I do not think slathering your logo onto every surface is a professional way to advertise your business(though it is certainly effective). I do want you, the customer, to know the name Vexxxer Munitions, but I'm not going to throw it in your face at every opportunity. I did try to put the logo inside the can on the lid, to make them more circumspect, but there are very odd ridges to make the cans stronger, and they interfere with my hand-stamping process.

If you have any comments on those two theoretical products especially, or if you have an idea that's even better, please email me. I am always open to customer suggestion. I hope to implement a quasi-forum on the store website for just this purpose, but for now emails will suffice.




Cheers Armslist, and happy hunting!




Thomas
Vexxxer Munitions

E. Bements & Sons, Lancing Michigan

FOR SALE is a very rare E. Bements & Son’s Lansing Michigan “PALACE OAK” #163, Cast Iron Parlor Stove.  This E. Bements & Son’s parlor stove is rare and you don’t see many of these anymore, dates back to between 1880 to 1892 and were considered to be one of the premier quality stoves at that time, it also heated evenly and conserved fuel. This stove has been disassembled, cleaned down to bare metal, repainted on the outside with a high gloss high quality heat paint (black & silver), on the inside flat black paint and has a minimum of 6 coats of paint on each piece of metal and meticulously reassembled (this stove is solid).  All cast iron metal and fire box is in great condition, super clean. I don’t know much about these types of stoves but I do know it looked great in my house and always a conversation piece.  I have owned this stove for many years, never lit a fire in it just kept it as a decorative display piece in my living room and just now this winter had it refinished. The stove body and the leg section are two separate pieces; the body sits on top of the leg section just the way it was when manufactured. 

This parlor stove is extremely ornate and has a very unique design from top to bottom also has some really nice features they are as follows:  3 large removable working doors with new mica glass, stove lid plate, 18“ fire box, 16” fire pot, fire chamber inside of stove is 16“ wide x 32“ tall, 4 shaker grates, removable top that exposes the stove lid plate covering the fire chamber, 26” x 26” foot print and 60” tall with a weight of 230 lbs., just an awesome stove. This parlor stove would look great in a home, office, country club etc., just as it did in mine.    (I have more pictures upon request).        

NOTE: Please understand this parlor stove is sold “AS IS” also I assume NO LIBILITY if you decide to light a fire in this parlor stove or use this stove for heating purposes. title: For Sale:  Bulk Ammo - Most Common Calibers - 100-round Brick Deal
postcontent:
Greetings Armslisters,




I have just opened the doors to Vexxxer Munitions(metaphorically; we don't actually have doors yet), and to celebrate I am posting the current stock of ammunition on Armslist, three weeks before our scheduled 'opening' ceremony, here in lovely Portland, OR. I should note right off the bat that this is an online-only store; we do not have a physical office address for one to come pick up ammunition, at least not yet. But you're not here to listen to ramblings about a green-as-grass munitions company, you're here to buy ammunition!


All ammunition is priced and sold in sets of 100 rounds. Shipping will be determined based on location and amount of rounds you want; buying more will end up saving you money, as I can pack them all into a single box, instead of 100 rounds per small box. 

I also offer a 'penny-round' discount for orders of 1,000 rounds or more. At the 1,000 round mark, I take off a penny per round. It's not a huge discount, granted, but if you are planning on shooting a lot anyways, it will save you a fair bit of cash to buy in large quantities. It also makes it much easier on my end logistically, and thus the savings fall directly to the consumer. I try every day to get the best possible deal for the end-customer, in this case, you.


While I do not yet have ALL calibers(we do plan to carry all as soon as is practical), I do have the most commonly shot rounds in America, according to the 2013 arms industry census. I chose to maintain healthy stockpiles of common calibers, rather than create a single brick per caliber, and have to fight to keep them stocked. So, without further preamble, I currently have in stock:


-Tula .45ACP


-Wolf 7.62x39mm


-Silver Bear .223/5.56 NATO


-Winchester Super-X 12GA, Buck-shot


-Bulgarian 7.62x54R, Silver-Tipped [CORROSIVE]


[A quick word on the corrosive ammunition; I am a huge Mosin fan, if you need any advice or assistance in keeping your Mosin pristine, while using the vastly cheaper surplus ammunition(the secret is boiling water), don't hestitate to send me an email. I'm more than happy to help out fellow gun enthusiasts, and Mosiners in particular]


I will be taking special notice of obtaining 9mm especially, as well as .22LR, .308, 10GA rounds as soon as possible, I know that I am missing these very common calibers. But as I said before I'd rather have a healthy stockpile of fewer calibers; the last thing I want is for someone to contact me, and me to be fresh out of any rounds they were looking to buy.



PROCESS:


To order(while our website is being constructed, at least) is very simple; email me with how many rounds you would like, of what caliber. I will require a state or military-issued ID as proof of age (sorry kids, no bullets for you!). From there, I will send you a shipping quote, NOT an estimate. There is an important distinction there; estimates can change, quotes will not. Most ammunition companies use an estimator, and charge you the final price halfway through the process, whether or not the estimate was correct. As I am not trying to profit off both the ammunition and shipping, I do not play the 'estimate' game; if I make a mistake, I will eat the cost; what I quote is what you pay, no exceptions. I'd rather lose money and keep a customer, and keep money and lose a customer.


Once we have the final cost and a formalized request for rounds, I will send you an invoice via Paypal. Once payment is received, you will receive an email from Paypal with the tracking number and current status of your order. Unfortunately, as many of you are no doubt aware, munitions by law MUST travel via ground, otherwise known as snail-mail. So please, factor in at least a week for shipping. That being said, I will ship the same day generally that your order is placed, and on rare occasions the next day. I discount Sunday completely, as no shipping company works on Sundays, much to the world's chagrin.


[For the unfamiliar: Paypal is an escrow service that watches over the transaction, protecting both you and I in exchange for a small fee from me. It is a completely free service for you, and takes about 5 minutes to create an account.]


From that point, all you have to do is wait. Your package will arrive(please notify me when it does; I'm timing various shipping companies to find the fastest ground transport. Also email me if there is something wrong; I'm here for my customers, if there's a problem, I want to know about it), and then all you need to do is go out and have a blast! No pun intended.



Building A Better Business:


Before I wrap up, a word on pricing. I am fully aware that the prices are high, and I am working on it. The bottleneck at this moment is waiting for the various munition factories to analyze and accept my business identification, to confirm that yes, I am a business in the realm of ammunition, and no, I am not just some guy trying to buy 10,000 rounds of ammunition for his 'hunting' trips. Prices and ammunition availability are different for licensed businesses and private citizens. Expect to see prices drop slightly within a month, and drop significantly within 7 months. It may be sooner but I'd rather be conservative in my estimates. The ads will change the very hour I get confirmation from the factories.




Feel free to email me with any questions, comments or concerns you might have. I hope to have a long business career supplying Americans with all their favorite calibers(please note I cannot ship international, at all, by law. Would if I could, but I can't, so I shan't). 


And, as a squeaky-clean, brand-new company, I would be remiss in my duties if I did not ask the customer; if you have any ideas or thoughts on how to run it more efficiently, cut down on shipping time, make the process easier for the customer, etc, please, my email is always open, and I check it multiple times a day. I would also love to hear your opinions on the 'brick' system, as well as my 'can' system that will go into effect next month. If I may tug on your ear a moment longer:

-I plan to have two basic types of product; bricks of 100 rounds, and ammo cans(with number of rounds dependent on caliber). So for example, 300 7.62x54R rounds fit perfectly into a .30 caliber ammunition can, and pricing would be based on how many rounds are included(the cans are free, a thank you for your business). The cans are all brand-new, un-stenciled; I chose this method to allow you to use them for other rounds and not have confusing stenciling on each box(claiming your ammo can full of 9mm is in fact 40mm explosive rounds, for example). I also chose to put the company brand on the back of the can, as I do not think slathering your logo onto every surface is a professional way to advertise your business(though it is certainly effective). I do want you, the customer, to know the name Vexxxer Munitions, but I'm not going to throw it in your face at every opportunity. I did try to put the logo inside the can on the lid, to make them more circumspect, but there are very odd ridges to make the cans stronger, and they interfere with my hand-stamping process.

If you have any comments on those two theoretical products especially, or if you have an idea that's even better, please email me. I am always open to customer suggestion. I hope to implement a quasi-forum on the store website for just this purpose, but for now emails will suffice.




Cheers Armslist, and happy hunting!




Thomas
Vexxxer Munitions

postcontent:
No more having to swap hands to reload. No more keeping a bullet or other tool in your pocket. No more having your tool slip off your finger or squeeze it too hard. No more getting your leg wacked by a tool attached to a retractable chain. Most importantly, no more accidentally committing a felony by leaving your tool attached to your bullet button. 

 The tool mounts to "virtually any" stamped aluminum or plastic magazine. The cap is made from plastic to help protect your AR-15 from scratches and it can be replaced if its damaged or wears out. This simple to use system is a "MUST SEE" for any bullet button AR user. 

 All research done on the CA DOJ website, as well as feedback from gun shop owners, parts dealers, and contributors to previous Calguns.net threads, indicate that this tool complies with CA DOJ regulations. What makes it compliant is that once a modified magazine is inserted into the mag-well it becomes part of the rifle, rendering the tool "unusable". It still requires another modified magazine (or other tool) to remove the magazine from the rifle. However, it is not officially approved by CA DOJ.

 Package included: 
 4 x Alloy Steel Screw
 4 x Black Plastic Cap
 1 x L Hex Key

 *Payment via Paypal, Price included shippping*

title: For Sale:  WALTHER PPK/S 380 ACP, like new, Stainless, not PP PPK PPKS
postcontent: ----SOLD----Walther PPK/S .380, Stainless Steel, 2 Magazines, Carry Case and Holster, serial number 3555AAA. From the production history and markings the pistol appears produced, under the first year of S&W licensing, at Black Creek, Gadsden, Alabama, but before S&W put its own serial numbers on Walther licensed PPK’s likely in 2000 or 2001. The serialization neither matches Interarms nor S&W numbering systems. The pistol has a short tang, the standard Walther markings and the “VA” proofing mark of Interarms appears on the receiver in the ejection port. In the interim period between the end of the Interarms license (1999) and the beginning of S&W "manufacturing" (2001) pistols continued to be made in Gadsden, Alabama by Black Creek, or Mid-South, companies under the S&W license from Walther (Umarex) apparently using various marked component parts. Records show that 6,600 pistols were manufactured in .380acp at Black Creek in 2000. The suffix “AAA” could represent: first 10,000 series, stainless, Alabama, or simply be filler. These transitional American PPK’s need to be recognized and valued as a variation, as distinct from the more common serial numbered German made, Interarms licensed, or later fully-marked and numbered S&W variations.

title: For Sale:  Prime Bullet Casting Lead
postcontent:
I have here over 300 lbs of bullet casting lead laboriously dug from the backstop of an outdoor rifle/pistol range.  This has been lovingly melted over a roaring gas flame, fluxed repeatedly during the melting process and the resulting crud skimmed off.  The molten lead was cast into ingots weighing approx. 2½ and 4¾ lbs. each.  Ingots are 7" long and either 1¾" or 2½" wide and will fit any of the common electric melting pots by Lyman, Lee or RCBS and other makers.

I had one batch of this alloy analyzed and it tests Antimony 1.49%, Tin .23, Lead 92.94, Copper .27 with the balance being traces of Iron, Bismuth and other metals in insignificant quantities.  I am assuming that the analysis remains fairly constant as it is all coming from the same section of the range but I make no guarantee of that.

Add 1% additional Tin to this and it will work for just about any handgun bullets and most rifle bullets to 1500 fps. if gas checked.  As it is it does fine for handgun bullets at under 1,000 fps but needs to be cast a little hotter than normal to get good fillout.   BHN is around 10.

Any quantity you want, picked up in Milton for $1.10/lb.  Shipping can be arranged via USPS Flat Rate Box, $5.00 to cover the cost of packaging + actual shipping costs for up to 65 lbs.
